---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Section from "@/components/Section.astro";
import AppStoreButton from "@/components/AppStoreButton.astro";

const title = "AR Wi-Fi Survey & Insights — How WiFi Buddy works";
const description =
  "WiFi Buddy uses ARKit world tracking to plot a real-time Wi-Fi heatmap as you walk, then a deterministic insights engine grades the survey, finds dead zones, and tells you what to change first.";
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <Section pad="lg">
    <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-wider text-[--color-signal-blue]">Features</p>
    <h1 class="mt-2 font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold tracking-tight leading-tight">
      Walk your home in AR. Get a graded Wi-Fi report. Know what to fix.
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg text-[--color-fg-muted]">
      WiFi Buddy is built around a single insight: a number on a screen
      tells you nothing about <em>where</em> your signal dies. Mapping
      latency to a real walked path turns a fuzzy "Wi-Fi feels slow"
      complaint into a list of specific rooms and specific fixes.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section pad="md">
    <div class="grid gap-10 md:grid-cols-5" data-reveal-stagger>
      <div class="md:col-span-3">
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">
          AR walk-and-paint survey
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-[--color-fg-muted]">
          The Survey tab uses Apple's <strong>ARWorldTrackingConfiguration</strong>
          (the same engine that powers Apple's Measure app and AR
          shopping) to track your iPhone's position in real-world meters.
          As you walk, your position is projected onto a 2D floor plan
          and TCP-latency probes are fired at Google DNS in the
          background. Each sample becomes a colored dot — green for
          excellent, amber for fair, red for a dead zone.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3 text-[--color-fg-muted]">
          To start: tap your starting position on the floor plan, hit
          <em>Start Survey</em>, and walk. Need to correct drift after a
          long walk? Tap <em>Re-anchor Here</em> and tap the spot on the
          map you're standing in — WiFi Buddy will also infer the map
          rotation from the first re-anchor segment so you don't have to
          tell the app "which way is forward".
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3 text-[--color-fg-muted]">
          When you stop, the trail and heatmap stay on the map for
          review. Pinch to zoom, drag to pan, and tap any waypoint to
          see the exact latency captured at that step.
        </p>
      </div>
      <aside class="md:col-span-2 card p-6">
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[--color-fg-dim]">Why AR</p>
        <h3 class="mt-2 font-display text-lg font-semibold">Pedometer + compass isn't accurate enough</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[--color-fg-muted]">
          Earlier prototypes used Core Motion's pedometer with magnetic
          heading. Indoors, magnetic heading drifts badly (rebar,
          appliances, the laptop you're holding) and the pedometer
          quantizes too coarsely for room-scale resolution. ARKit's
          visual-inertial odometry uses the camera and the IMU together,
          which is dramatically more stable indoors.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[--color-fg-muted]">
          The camera feed is used by ARKit only — it is never recorded,
          screenshotted, or sent anywhere.
        </p>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section pad="md">
    <div data-reveal>
      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        The Insights Engine: a real report, not a heatmap
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-3 max-w-3xl text-[--color-fg-muted]">
        Most heatmap apps stop at colored dots. WiFi Buddy runs a
        <strong>SurveyInsightsEngine</strong> over your trail when you stop
        walking. It's a pure-Swift, on-device analytics pass that produces
        a graded report — same trail in, same report out, every time.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-8 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3" data-reveal-stagger>
      <div class="card p-6">
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[--color-fg-dim]">Step 1</p>
        <h3 class="mt-2 font-display text-lg font-semibold">Score &amp; grade</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[--color-fg-muted]">
          A weighted score (60% coverage mix, 40% median latency, with a
          p95 spike penalty) maps to an A–F grade plus a one-sentence
          headline so the user understands the grade at a glance.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="card p-6">
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[--color-fg-dim]">Step 2</p>
        <h3 class="mt-2 font-display text-lg font-semibold">Cluster dead zones</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[--color-fg-muted]">
          Single-link clustering with a 1.8 m merge threshold groups poor
          samples into named dead zones — "2 dead zones (master closet,
          back patio)" instead of an ambiguous fog of red dots.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="card p-6">
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[--color-fg-dim]">Step 3</p>
        <h3 class="mt-2 font-display text-lg font-semibold">Recommend</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[--color-fg-muted]">
          A tailored "what to do next" list — mesh vs. extender vs.
          reposition vs. channel change vs. 5 GHz switch — keyed off
          dead-zone count, jitter ratio, and median latency.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-10 card p-6 md:p-8" data-reveal>
      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold">Insights the engine surfaces</h3>
      <ul class="mt-4 grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2 text-sm text-[--color-fg-muted]">
        <li>
          <strong class="text-[--color-fg]">Coverage breakdown.</strong> Excellent /
          fair / poor percentages with a stacked bar.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-[--color-fg]">Dead-zone count.</strong> Worst zone
          highlighted by sample count and latency.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-[--color-fg]">Latency profile.</strong> Catches the
          "median is fine but p95 is awful" case that plain averages
          miss — the one-bad-room failure mode that drops video calls.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-[--color-fg]">Stability warning.</strong> Fires only
          when jitter/median ≥ 0.5 <em>and</em> jitter ≥ 20 ms — so a 3
          ms wobble on a 25 ms baseline doesn't trigger a false alarm.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-[--color-fg]">Router direction hint.</strong> Pearson
          correlation between distance-from-start and latency. Surfaced
          only when |r| ≥ 0.35 and you've walked ≥ 3 m.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-[--color-fg]">What to do next.</strong> Mesh vs.
          reposition vs. 5 GHz switch — concrete, not generic.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section pad="md">
    <div class="grid gap-8 md:grid-cols-2" data-reveal-stagger>
      <div>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">
          Real speed test, real ISP context
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-[--color-fg-muted]">
          The Speed tab runs a four-phase test: server selection → ping →
          download → upload. Download and upload each use 8 concurrent
          streams against Cloudflare for true throughput, and we surface
          the chosen Cloudflare colo plus your ISP — so when an ISP
          routes your test traffic 800+ miles to a distant POP, you see
          it instead of blaming your Wi-Fi.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">
          Live network topology
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-[--color-fg-muted]">
          ISP → Router → Device, each hop with its own real-time TCP
          latency probe and traffic-light health classification. The
          packet-flow connectors animate only while a hop is actually
          carrying traffic — so a glance at the dashboard tells you
          whether your problem is upstream of the router or inside your
          home.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section pad="md">
    <div class="card p-8 md:p-10" data-reveal>
      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        Klaus, your AI Wi-Fi sidekick
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-3 max-w-3xl text-[--color-fg-muted]">
        Klaus is a pixel-art assistant fronting a curated knowledge base
        of 24 home-Wi-Fi questions — coverage, gaming, streaming,
        security, mesh upgrades, MAC randomization, port forwarding, and
        more. He doesn't call an LLM and he doesn't make a single
        network request: it's a deterministic keyword scorer over
        hand-written answers, so the same question always gets the same
        explanation. Free users get one question per install; Pro
        unlocks unlimited chat.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 max-w-3xl text-[--color-fg-muted]">
        The motivation is simple: AI assistants in utility apps tend to
        overpromise and underdeliver. A focused FAQ with personality
        beats a flaky chatbot that hallucinates router model numbers.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section pad="md">
    <div class="card p-8 md:p-10 flex flex-col items-start gap-4" data-reveal>
      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        Try it on your own home.
      </h2>
      <p class="text-[--color-fg-muted]">
        Free Speed, Signal &amp; Devices tabs. WiFi Buddy Pro from
        {/* Pricing pulled from src/lib/site.ts so it stays in sync */}
        <strong class="text-[--color-fg]">$3.99/mo</strong> with a
        3-day free trial.
      </p>
      <AppStoreButton size="lg" class="cta-press" />
    </div>
  </Section>
</BaseLayout>
